Self-assessment experiment data analysis

Carlos Granell

15/04/2020 (updated 17 abril, 2020)

This document analyses the responses of a pre-questionnaire and (soon) a post-questionnaire as part of the experiment Reproducibility of GIScience MSc Theses - Self-assessment experiment - see OSF project

Reproduce paper

To create the PDF of the computational notebook you can run the following commands in a new R session. If you have problems rendering the PDF you can execute each chunk independently in RStudio.

Software dependencies and code

This document does not install the required R packages by default. You can run the script install.R to install all required dependencies on a new R installation, or use install.packages(..) to install missing R packages.

Required libraries and runtime environment description are as follows.

library("tidyverse")
library("forcats")
library("kableExtra")
library("here")
library("googlesheets4")
library("likert")

Download raw survey data

Pre-test assessment

The following plots are based on the file C:/MyCode/self-assessment-experiment/data-raw/pre-test.csv, filtered by students from MSc in Geospatial Technologies (UJI, NOVA IMS, IFGI-WWU) and MSc Geomatics (TU Delft).

MSc in Geospatial Technologies (UJI, NOVA IMS, IFGI-WWU)

13 students answered the pre-questionnaire.

3 students have been previously trained on reproducible research practices.

If you answered YES in either of the last two questions, please explain which were the MAIN DIFFICULTIES you experienced. If NO, skip question Do you know where to look for HELP and extra information to make your research reproducible? Section 2: Current working practices

Note that responses to working practices were multi-choice (N=13).
Practice group - Survey question
analysis What tools do you plan to use to ANALYSE data?
visualisation What tools do you plan to use to VISUALISE/PLOT data?
writing What tools do you plan to WRITE UP your master thesis or conference/journal article?
workflow What is your (expected) process of GETTING the summary data, statistical results, figures, maps and tables IN your master thesis document (or conference/journal article)?
